%YAML 1.1
%TAG !u! tag:unity3d.com,2011:
--- !u!114 &11400000
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 41efd3a8d3679a34abb3d50a57175293, type: 3}
  m_Name: NewChallenge
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ChallengeData
  challengeId: phishing_01
  title: 'Suspicious Email '
  description: You stumble across a suspicious email
  challengeType: 0
  difficultyTier: 1
  options:
  - text: 'Click the "Verify Now" button Immediately '
    isCorrect: 0
    feedbackNarrative: You acted under pressure without verifying the sender's authenticity.
      The website was a credential harvesting page. Your login details have been
      compromised. Always validate suspicious emails before interacting with embedded
      links.
  - text: Hover over the link to inspect the URL before clicking
    isCorrect: 1
    feedbackNarrative: You inspected the hyperlink and noticed the domain does not
      match the official institution website. Hovering over links before clicking
      is a strong defensive habit against phishing attacks.
  - text: Check the sender's email domain carefully
    isCorrect: 1
    feedbackNarrative: The sender domain "tp-studentverify.com" is not an official
      institutional domain. Attackers often register lookalike domains to impersonate
      legitimate organizations. Domain verification is a critical detection technique.
  - text: Ignore the email completely
    isCorrect: 1
    feedbackNarrative: While you avoided interacting with a phishing email, ignoring
      potential security alerts is not ideal. The safest action would be to verify
      the email through official channels or report it.
  - text: Forward the email to official IT Security team
    isCorrect: 1
    feedbackNarrative: Excellent decisions. Reporting suspected phishing attempts
      help protect the wider prganization. Security teams rely on early reporting
      to block malicious domains to prevent further compromise.
  - text: Reply to the email asking if it is legitimate
    isCorrect: 0
    feedbackNarrative: Replying confirms to the attacker that your email address
      is active, increasing your risk of future targeted attacks. Never engage directly
      with suspicious senders.
  emails:
  - senderName: Temasek Polytechnic IT Helpdesk
    senderAddress: support@tp-studentverify.com
    subject: 'URGENT: Student Portal Access Suspended'
    body: 'Dear Student,


      We detected multiple suspicious login attempts on
      your student portal account from an overseas IP address.

      For security
      reasons, your access has been temporarily suspended.

      You must verify
      your identity within 2 hours to avoid permanent account deactivation before
      the examination release window.


      Click the link below to restore access
      immediately:

      https://tp-studentverify.com/secure-login


      Failure
      to comply may result in loss of exam access privileges.


      IT Helpdesk

      Temasek
      Polytechnic'
    isPhishing: 1
    phishingClues: "- Sender domain does not match official institution domain\n-
      Urgency and time pressure (\u201Cwithin 2 hours\u201D)\n- Threat of severe
      consequence (exam access loss)\n- Generic greeting (\u201CDear Student\u201D)\n-
      External link domain mismatch"
  consequenceNarrative: You clicked the verification link and entered your login
    credentials. The website was a spoofed credential harvesting page controlled
    by attackers. Within minutes, your real account password was changed. The attacker
    accessed your student records and attempted lateral access to other institutional
    systems.
  consequenceType: 0
  debriefText: "This email demonstrates classic phishing techniques:\n\n- Domain
    Spoofing \u2013 Attackers register lookalike domains to mimic legitimate organizations.\n-
    Artificial Urgency \u2013 Time pressure reduces rational decision-making.\n-
    Authority Impersonation \u2013 Pretending to be IT support increases compliance.\n-
    Credential Harvesting \u2013 Fake login portals capture usernames and passwords.\n\nBest
    Practice:\n\n- Never click embedded links in urgent emails.\n- Manually navigate
    to the official website instead.\n- Verify sender domains carefully.\n- Report
    suspicious emails to the security team."
  realWorldStat: According to the Cyber Security Agency of Singapore, phishing remains
    one of the top reported cybercrimes in Singapore, with thousands of cases annually
    involving impersonation of trusted institutions and credential theft.
